  <li id="comment-698" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/09362230114603439603" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Bonnie</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2004/08/i-took-deep-breaths/#comment-698"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2007-07-07T00:08:00-04:00">Saturday, July 7, 2007 at 12:08 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Several years ago I devised a similar recipe (mine has a bit of sweetner and flavoring).  I make them with dried cherries and almonds (with almond extract) and fresh and frozen cranberries with vanilla and ground cloves, for a couple of favorites.  </></>What I really wanted to contribute is my way of dealing with the sticky dough.  I use rice flour when shaping the scones.  Any type will do but the coarser grind makes for a crunchy surface while a finer grind is almost un-noticeable.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-698' data-commentid="698" data-postid="1829" data-belowelement="comment-698" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Bonnie" aria-label='Reply to Bonnie'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
